
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dig` (domain information groper) baraye query kardan DNS server-ha estefade mishavad. Be zaban sade, ba `dig` mitoonid etela'ati dar morede domain-ha (masalan IP address, MX record, etc.) az DNS server-ha begirid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dig example.com` --> 🤔  Query kardan IP address A record baraye example.com.
    🔹 `dig example.com MX` --> 📧 Query kardan MX record baraye example.com (mail exchange).
    🔹 `dig example.com NS` --> 🌐 Query kardan NS record baraye example.com (name server).
    🔹 `dig +trace example.com` --> 🔭 Trace kardan path query az root DNS server ta javab.
    🔹 `dig -x <IP address>` --> 📍 Reverse DNS lookup, peida kardan name domain az IP address.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dig google.com

    🔹  Namayesh IP address google.com az DNS server pishfarz.

    $ dig @8.8.8.8 google.com

    🔹  Query kardan IP address google.com az DNS server 8.8.8.8 (Google's public DNS).

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dig example.com A +short

    🔹 Faghat IP address A record domain `example.com` ra namayesh midahad (bedune etela'ate ezafi).

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dig` (domain information groper) command is used to query DNS servers. Simply put, you can use `dig` to retrieve information about domains (e.g., IP address, MX record, etc.) from DNS servers.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dig example.com` --> 🤔 Query the A record IP address for example.com.
    🔹 `dig example.com MX` --> 📧 Query the MX record for example.com (mail exchange).
    🔹 `dig example.com NS` --> 🌐 Query the NS record for example.com (name server).
    🔹 `dig +trace example.com` --> 🔭 Trace the query path from the root DNS server to the answer.
    🔹 `dig -x <IP address>` --> 📍 Perform a reverse DNS lookup to find the domain name from an IP address.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dig google.com

    🔹 Display the IP address of google.com from the default DNS server.

    $ dig @8.8.8.8 google.com

    🔹 Query the IP address of google.com from DNS server 8.8.8.8 (Google's public DNS).

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dig example.com A +short

    🔹 Displays only the A record IP address of the `example.com` domain (without extra information).
